1
00:00:23,824 --> 00:00:24,992
Positions!

2
00:00:38,739 --> 00:00:39,873
(BEEPING)

3
00:00:42,175 --> 00:00:43,310
(POWER HUMMING)

4
00:00:43,410 --> 00:00:44,778
'Night, boys.

5
00:01:36,063 --> 00:01:38,365
(CREAKING)

6
00:01:53,647 --> 00:01:55,449
(ALARM BLARING)

7
00:02:01,955 --> 00:02:03,457
(SIREN WAILING)

8
00:02:04,524 --> 00:02:06,493
(MEN CHATTERING)

9
00:02:08,695 --> 00:02:10,163
Sorry, lover.

10
00:02:10,263 --> 00:02:11,698
(SIREN WAILING)

11
00:02:35,989 --> 00:02:37,891
We've got the place surrounded, sir.

12
00:02:49,703 --> 00:02:51,505
Hello. I'm so terribly sorry.

13
00:02:51,605 --> 00:02:54,374
That card-paying-device thing,
that's a Lobster card, am I right?

14
00:02:54,474 --> 00:02:56,910
-Oyster card.
-Ah, well, that's the problem, you see.

15
00:02:57,010 --> 00:02:59,179
I only use my Oyster
when there's an "R" in the month.

16
00:02:59,246 --> 00:03:00,313
It's April.

17
00:03:00,414 --> 00:03:01,515
(SIRENS WAILING)

18
00:03:01,581 --> 00:03:02,749
Go, go, go!

19
00:03:03,150 --> 00:03:05,352
Diamonds. Genuine.

20
00:03:08,088 --> 00:03:10,657
-Drive.
-Works for me.

21
00:03:14,795 --> 00:03:16,329
No sign of her on the pavement.

22
00:03:16,830 --> 00:03:18,331
Just in time, mate!

23
00:03:20,133 --> 00:03:21,268
(BEEPS)

24
00:03:30,744 --> 00:03:33,146
Hello, I'm the Doctor. Happy Easter!

25
00:03:35,348 --> 00:03:37,017
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

26
00:04:10,450 --> 00:04:11,985
(SIREN WAILING)

27
00:04:12,085 --> 00:04:14,988
Right, close off the area.
Get all these people cleared.

28
00:04:15,088 --> 00:04:16,690
She's got to be here somewhere.

29
00:04:16,790 --> 00:04:19,626
Robinson, clear the road!
Get the whole place sealed off.

30
00:04:19,726 --> 00:04:21,161
She's on the bus. She's on the...

31
00:04:21,261 --> 00:04:25,132
Come on, get the car.
It's definitely her, come on. Move it.

32
00:04:25,699 --> 00:04:27,701
Jackson, follow that bus!

33
00:04:30,137 --> 00:04:31,538
(SIRENS WAILING)

34
00:04:37,144 --> 00:04:39,479
Funny thing is, I don't often do Easter,
I can never find it.

35
00:04:39,579 --> 00:04:43,483
It's always at a different time.
Although, I remember the original.

36
00:04:43,583 --> 00:04:44,951
Between you and me,
what really happened was...

37
00:04:45,018 --> 00:04:46,086
(BEEPING)

38
00:04:46,186 --> 00:04:47,954
Oh, sorry, hold on to that for me.

39
00:04:48,889 --> 00:04:50,423
Actually, go on, have it, finish it.

40
00:04:50,524 --> 00:04:53,693
It's full of sugar and I'm determined
to keep these teeth.

41
00:04:53,794 --> 00:04:54,861
Ah!

42
00:04:55,462 --> 00:04:57,564
Oh, we've got excitation!

43
00:04:57,664 --> 00:04:58,932
(BEEPING)

44
00:04:59,032 --> 00:05:01,234
I'm picking up something very strange.

45
00:05:01,334 --> 00:05:02,402
(STATIC WARBLING)

46
00:05:02,502 --> 00:05:04,171
I know the feeling.

47
00:05:04,805 --> 00:05:06,373
(SIRENS WAILING)

48
00:05:06,873 --> 00:05:11,144
All units in pursuit,
registration Whisky 974,

49
00:05:11,244 --> 00:05:14,147
Golf, Hotel, Mike. They're heading
for the Gladwell Road Tunnel.

50
00:05:14,247 --> 00:05:17,250
Please stop all traffic,
seal off the north end.

51
00:05:20,554 --> 00:05:22,756
The bus has entered
the south entrance of the tunnel.

52
00:05:22,856 --> 00:05:24,090
Officers in pursuit.

53
00:05:24,191 --> 00:05:26,860
Units now arriving
at the north entrance.

54
00:05:30,931 --> 00:05:33,200
(CHATTERING ON POLICE RADIO)

55
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:35,235
Tango 183 at the far end, sir.

56
00:05:35,335 --> 00:05:38,471
I've sealed off the exit.
There's no way out, over.

57
00:05:41,675 --> 00:05:43,677
I'm right behind. We've got her.

58
00:05:43,777 --> 00:05:46,146
Rhondium particles,
that's what I'm looking for.

59
00:05:46,246 --> 00:05:48,248
This thing detects them.

60
00:05:48,348 --> 00:05:50,450
The little dish should go round,
that little dish there.

61
00:05:50,550 --> 00:05:52,752
Right now, a way out
would come in pretty handy.

62
00:05:52,853 --> 00:05:54,855
Can you detect me one of those?

63
00:05:56,456 --> 00:05:58,792
CARMEN: Lou, can you hear them?

64
00:05:59,392 --> 00:06:01,895
-Hear what, sweetheart?
-The voices.

65
00:06:02,329 --> 00:06:05,165
So many voices. Calling to us.

66
00:06:05,265 --> 00:06:06,566
(VOICES WHISPERING)

67
00:06:06,666 --> 00:06:08,134
Calling so far.

68
00:06:09,202 --> 00:06:12,806
-Oh, the little dish is going round!
-Fascinating.

69
00:06:14,975 --> 00:06:17,310
And round. Oh!

70
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:21,681
-Excuse me. Do you mind?
-Sorry, that was my little dish.

71
00:06:21,781 --> 00:06:23,950
Can't you turn that thing off?

72
00:06:24,551 --> 00:06:26,286
-What was your name?
-Christina.

73
00:06:26,386 --> 00:06:28,488
Christina, hold on tight.

74
00:06:28,688 --> 00:06:29,923
Everyone! Hold on!

75
00:06:30,023 --> 00:06:31,491
(ALL SCREAMING)

76
00:06:31,591 --> 00:06:33,126
(CRASHING)

77
00:06:33,226 --> 00:06:37,497
The voices! The voices!
They're screaming!

78
00:06:42,135 --> 00:06:43,737
What's going on?

79
00:06:53,146 --> 00:06:54,814
(GLASS SHATTERING)

80
00:06:59,619 --> 00:07:02,289
Tango 183, units in position, sir.

81
00:07:03,890 --> 00:07:07,661
Uh, sorry to report,
but no sign of the bus, over.

82
00:07:08,428 --> 00:07:12,899
It's gone. Right in front of me.
The bus has just gone.

83
00:07:14,901 --> 00:07:15,936
Over.

84
00:07:50,470 --> 00:07:51,972
End of the line.

85
00:07:56,376 --> 00:08:00,647
Call it a hunch, but I think we've
gone a little bit further than Brixton.

86
00:08:17,530 --> 00:08:19,733
(CHIRRUPING)

87
00:08:22,369 --> 00:08:23,970
LOU: We should get out.

88
00:08:24,070 --> 00:08:27,841
Even if that's the Sahara,
we can't stay onboard this thing.

89
00:08:27,941 --> 00:08:29,809
I'm not going out there.

90
00:08:29,909 --> 00:08:32,946
They're still calling. All around us.

91
00:08:33,046 --> 00:08:34,948
(VOICES WHISPERING)

92
00:08:35,582 --> 00:08:38,518
The voices are crying.

93
00:08:38,618 --> 00:08:40,587
What voices, sweetheart?

94
00:08:41,421 --> 00:08:42,822
The dead.

95
00:08:44,657 --> 00:08:47,694
We are surrounded by the dead.

96
00:08:57,404 --> 00:09:01,775
That's impossible. There are three suns.
Three of 'em!

97
00:09:02,208 --> 00:09:04,411
Like when all those planets
were up in the sky!

98
00:09:04,511 --> 00:09:06,880
But it was the Earth
that moved back then, wasn't it?

99
00:09:06,980 --> 00:09:08,982
Oh, man, we're on another world!

100
00:09:09,082 --> 00:09:10,850
DRIVER: It's still intact, though.

101
00:09:10,950 --> 00:09:13,887
Not as bad as it looks, though,
the chassis is still holding together.

102
00:09:13,987 --> 00:09:16,156
Oh, my boss is gonna murder me!

103
00:09:16,256 --> 00:09:17,490
Can you still drive it?

104
00:09:17,590 --> 00:09:21,928
Oh, no, no. The wheels are stuck.
Look at them, they're never gonna budge.

105
00:09:22,028 --> 00:09:24,864
Dennison, listen.
We've sealed off the far end.

106
00:09:24,964 --> 00:09:27,267
Nothing is to come through.

107
00:09:27,367 --> 00:09:29,903
But I don't understand, sir.
How can a bus just disappear?

108
00:09:31,137 --> 00:09:33,206
Ready for every emergency.

109
00:09:37,710 --> 00:09:39,446
(MECHANICAL BUZZING)

110
00:09:41,414 --> 00:09:42,916
Me, too!

111
00:09:43,016 --> 00:09:45,251
-And what's your name?
-I'm the Doctor.

112
00:09:45,351 --> 00:09:47,253
-Name, not rank.
-The Doctor.

113
00:09:47,353 --> 00:09:48,588
-Surname?
-The Doctor.

114
00:09:48,688 --> 00:09:51,324
-You're called "The Doctor"?
-Yes, I am.

115
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:54,627
That's not a name,
that's a psychological condition.

116
00:09:54,727 --> 00:09:58,331
Funny sort of sand, this.
There's a trace of something else.

117
00:09:59,332 --> 00:10:01,668
(EXCLAIMING IN DISGUST)

118
00:10:02,001 --> 00:10:05,305
-Blah, that's not good.
-Well, it wouldn't be, it's sand.

119
00:10:05,405 --> 00:10:07,173
No, it tastes like...

120
00:10:08,842 --> 00:10:11,511
-Never mind.
-What is it, what's wrong?

121
00:10:12,011 --> 00:10:15,715
Hold on a minute. I saw you, mate!
You had that thing, that machine.

122
00:10:15,815 --> 00:10:16,983
Did you make this happen?

123
00:10:17,083 --> 00:10:19,519
Oh, humans on buses, always blaming me.

124
00:10:19,619 --> 00:10:20,920
Look, look, if you must know,

125
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:23,556
I was tracking a hole
in the fabric of reality.

126
00:10:23,656 --> 00:10:27,627
Call it a hobby. But it was a tiny,
little hole, no danger to anyone.

127
00:10:27,727 --> 00:10:29,762
Suddenly it gets big
and we drive right through it.

128
00:10:29,863 --> 00:10:31,431
Then where is it?

129
00:10:31,531 --> 00:10:34,734
There's nothing, there's just sand!

130
00:10:35,535 --> 00:10:37,137
DOCTOR: All right.

131
00:10:39,906 --> 00:10:43,743
If you want proof,
we drove through this.

132
00:10:51,184 --> 00:10:52,485
What the hell was that?

133
00:10:53,486 --> 00:10:55,321
-And that's...
-A door.

134
00:10:56,656 --> 00:10:58,324
A door in space.

135
00:10:58,424 --> 00:11:01,294
So what you're saying is,
on the other side of that is home?

136
00:11:01,394 --> 00:11:03,229
We can get to London through there?

137
00:11:03,329 --> 00:11:05,832
The bus came through, but we can't.

138
00:11:05,932 --> 00:11:08,368
-Then what are we waiting for?
-No, no, don't.

139
00:11:08,468 --> 00:11:10,170
-I'm going home, mate!
-I said don't!

140
00:11:10,270 --> 00:11:11,571
(DRIVER SCREAMING)

141
00:11:11,671 --> 00:11:13,173
(CRACKLING)

142
00:11:20,046 --> 00:11:23,349
He was a skeleton, man!
He was bones, just bones.

143
00:11:23,449 --> 00:11:27,754
Dennison, uh, I think we're
out of our depth here.

144
00:11:27,854 --> 00:11:29,455
We need experts.

145
00:11:30,390 --> 00:11:33,326
Get me UNIT, Emergency Code One.

146
00:11:37,964 --> 00:11:41,000
The bus, look at the damage.

147
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:43,403
It was the bus protecting us.

148
00:11:43,503 --> 00:11:46,806
-Great big box of metal.
-Rather like a Faraday cage?

149
00:11:47,373 --> 00:11:49,776
Like in a thunderstorm, yeah?

150
00:11:50,043 --> 00:11:51,878
Safest place is inside a car,

151
00:11:51,978 --> 00:11:55,748
'cause the metal conducts the lightning
right through. We did it in school.

152
00:11:55,848 --> 00:11:58,351
But if we can only travel back
inside the bus...

153
00:11:58,451 --> 00:12:02,689
A Faraday cage needs to be closed.
That thing's been ripped wide open!

154
00:12:02,989 --> 00:12:04,524
Slightly different dynamics
with a wormhole.

155
00:12:04,624 --> 00:12:07,594
There's enough metal to make it work,
I think. I hope.

156
00:12:07,694 --> 00:12:09,662
Then we have to drive
five tonnes of bus,

157
00:12:09,762 --> 00:12:11,631
which is currently buried in the sand,

158
00:12:11,731 --> 00:12:14,200
and we've got nothing
but our bare hands, correct?

159
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:18,171
I'd say nine-and-a-half tonnes,
but the point still stands, yeah.

160
00:12:18,271 --> 00:12:20,640
Then we need to apply ourselves
to the problem with discipline.

161
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:23,810
-Which starts with appointing a leader.
-Yes, at last, thank you, so...

162
00:12:23,910 --> 00:12:25,311
Well, thank goodness you've got me.

163
00:12:25,411 --> 00:12:28,715
Everyone, do exactly as I say.
Inside the bus, immediately!

164
00:12:28,815 --> 00:12:31,918
-Is it safe in there?
-I don't think anything's safe any more.

165
00:12:32,018 --> 00:12:34,787
But if it's a choice between
baking in there or roasting out here,

166
00:12:34,887 --> 00:12:36,789
I'd say baking is slower.

167
00:12:36,889 --> 00:12:39,125
Come on. All of you, right now!

168
00:12:40,293 --> 00:12:42,428
And you, "The Doctor."

169
00:12:42,495 --> 00:12:43,830
Yes, ma'am.

170
00:12:44,364 --> 00:12:46,332
CHRISTINA: Up, come on.

171
00:12:49,168 --> 00:12:51,804
Point five,
the crucial thing is, do not panic.

172
00:12:51,904 --> 00:12:53,206
Quite apart from anything else,

173
00:12:53,306 --> 00:12:56,643
the smell of sweat inside this thing
is reaching atrocious levels.

174
00:12:56,743 --> 00:12:58,311
We don't need to add any more.

175
00:12:58,411 --> 00:13:00,747
Point six, team identification.

176
00:13:00,847 --> 00:13:03,182
Names, I'm Christina.

177
00:13:03,283 --> 00:13:05,852
-This man is apparently "The Doctor”.
-Hello.

178
00:13:05,952 --> 00:13:07,787
-And you?
-Nathan.

179
00:13:08,254 --> 00:13:11,057
-I'm Barclay.
-Angela, Angela Whittaker.

180
00:13:11,524 --> 00:13:15,628
My name's Louis, everyone calls me Lou,
and this is Carmen.

181
00:13:15,728 --> 00:13:18,965
Excellent. Memorise those names.
There might be a test.

182
00:13:19,065 --> 00:13:22,201
Point seven, assessment
and application of knowledge.

183
00:13:22,302 --> 00:13:24,704
Over to you, The Doctor.

184
00:13:24,804 --> 00:13:27,040
-I thought you were in charge.
-I am.

185
00:13:27,140 --> 00:13:29,442
And a good leader utilises her strength.

186
00:13:29,542 --> 00:13:33,379
You seem to be the brain box.
So, start boxing.

187
00:13:34,047 --> 00:13:37,583
Right. So, the wormhole.

188
00:13:37,684 --> 00:13:40,953
We were in the wrong place at the
wrong time, it was just an accident.

189
00:13:41,020 --> 00:13:43,189
No, it wasn't.

190
00:13:44,324 --> 00:13:49,862
That thing, the doorway,
someone made it for a reason.

191
00:13:50,463 --> 00:13:52,031
How do you know?

192
00:13:53,166 --> 00:13:54,867
LOU: She's got a gift.

193
00:13:54,967 --> 00:13:58,705
Ever since she was a little girl,
she can just tell things.

194
00:13:59,072 --> 00:14:02,942
-We do the lottery twice a week.
-You don't look like millionaires.

195
00:14:03,042 --> 00:14:05,044
No, but we win £10.

196
00:14:05,712 --> 00:14:08,448
Every week, twice a week, £10.

197
00:14:09,148 --> 00:14:11,384
Don't tell me that's not a gift.

198
00:14:11,684 --> 00:14:14,153
Tell me, Carmen.
How many fingers am I holding up?

199
00:14:14,220 --> 00:14:15,421
Three.

200
00:14:16,522 --> 00:14:18,624
-Four.
-Very good.

201
00:14:19,125 --> 00:14:22,695
Low-level psychic ability,
exacerbated by an alien sun.

202
00:14:23,529 --> 00:14:26,699
What can you see, Carmen?
Tell me, what's out there?

203
00:14:27,900 --> 00:14:31,738
Something... Something is coming.

204
00:14:31,871 --> 00:14:33,272
(VOICES WHISPERING)

205
00:14:33,373 --> 00:14:35,174
Riding on the wind.

206
00:14:36,109 --> 00:14:38,711
-And shining.
-What is it?

207
00:14:40,246 --> 00:14:41,414
Death.

208
00:14:42,482 --> 00:14:44,884
-Death is coming.
-We're going to die.

209
00:14:44,984 --> 00:14:47,220
Oh, I knew it, man. I said so.

210
00:14:47,353 --> 00:14:48,588
We can't die out here,
no one's gonna find us.

211
00:14:48,688 --> 00:14:50,990
-This isn't exactly helping.
-Shut up, we're not your soldiers.

212
00:14:51,090 --> 00:14:52,759
-It's not doing any good.
-You're upsetting her, be quiet.

213
00:14:52,859 --> 00:14:55,728
-Will we be bones, like the bus driver?
-CHRISTINA: Stop whimpering, all of you.

214
00:14:55,828 --> 00:14:57,897
All right, now stop it,
everyone, stop it!

215
00:14:57,964 --> 00:14:59,098
(SOBBING)

216
00:14:59,966 --> 00:15:03,469
Angela, look at me. Angela? Angela?
Answer me one question, Angela.

217
00:15:03,569 --> 00:15:06,472
That's it, at me, at me. There we go.

218
00:15:06,672 --> 00:15:08,674
Angela, just answer me one thing.

219
00:15:08,775 --> 00:15:11,778
When you got on this bus,
where were you going?

220
00:15:12,211 --> 00:15:14,947
-Doesn't matter now, does it?
-Answer the question.

221
00:15:15,047 --> 00:15:17,283
-Just home.
-And what's home?

222
00:15:17,650 --> 00:15:22,622
Me, and Mike and Suzanne,
that's my daughter. She's 18.

223
00:15:22,722 --> 00:15:25,658
Suzanne. Good. What about you?

224
00:15:26,492 --> 00:15:30,496
-I don't know. Going round Tina's.
-Who's Tina? Your girlfriend?

225
00:15:31,364 --> 00:15:32,465
Not yet.

226
00:15:32,565 --> 00:15:35,034
Good boy. What about you, Nathan?

227
00:15:35,134 --> 00:15:38,504
Bit strapped for cash,
I lost my job last week.

228
00:15:39,539 --> 00:15:42,074
I was gonna stay in. Watch TV.

229
00:15:42,175 --> 00:15:45,011
-Brilliant. And you two?
-I was going to cook.

230
00:15:45,111 --> 00:15:47,947
It's his turn tonight, then I clear up.

231
00:15:48,047 --> 00:15:50,349
-What's for tea?
-Chops.

232
00:15:50,950 --> 00:15:54,720
Nice couple of chops and gravy.
Nothing special.

233
00:15:54,821 --> 00:15:57,356
Oh, that's special, Lou.
That is so special.

234
00:15:57,457 --> 00:15:59,125
Chops and gravy. Mmm!

235
00:15:59,225 --> 00:16:01,160
What about you, Christina?

236
00:16:01,260 --> 00:16:05,031
I was going...so far away.

237
00:16:05,731 --> 00:16:09,035
Far away. Chops and gravy. Watching TV.
Mike and Suzanne, and poor old Tina.

238
00:16:09,135 --> 00:16:11,204
-Hey!
-Just think of them.

239
00:16:11,304 --> 00:16:13,172
'Cause that planet out there,

240
00:16:13,272 --> 00:16:17,410
all three suns and wormholes and
alien sand, that planet is nothing.

241
00:16:18,144 --> 00:16:22,048
You hear me? Nothing, compared to
all those things waiting for you.

242
00:16:23,049 --> 00:16:25,418
Food and home and people.

243
00:16:26,953 --> 00:16:28,421
Hold on to that.

244
00:16:30,056 --> 00:16:32,892
"Cause we're gonna get there, I promise.

245
00:16:34,894 --> 00:16:36,829
I'm gonna get you home.

246
00:16:39,131 --> 00:16:40,766
(HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING)

247
00:16:53,613 --> 00:16:55,281
MAN 1: Section one, assume position.

248
00:16:55,381 --> 00:16:57,483
Section two, assume position.

249
00:16:57,583 --> 00:17:01,187
MAN 2: Section three, assume position.
MAN 3: Section four, assume position.

250
00:17:01,287 --> 00:17:04,390
MAN 1: Spread out!
MAN 2: Take basic intervention mode.

251
00:17:06,325 --> 00:17:07,860
-Isolate the area!
-Yes, ma'am.

252
00:17:07,960 --> 00:17:09,962
Establish an exclusion zone.

253
00:17:10,062 --> 00:17:12,965
Any media, move them back.
Any trouble, arrest them.

254
00:17:13,065 --> 00:17:14,066
SOLDIER: Yes, ma'am.

255
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:17,169
I want the vehicles in a standard
Procedure Five layout.

256
00:17:17,270 --> 00:17:20,239
All outreach officers will report to me
via Sergeant Calhoun.

257
00:17:20,339 --> 00:17:21,541
-Is that understood?
-Yes, ma'am.

258
00:17:21,641 --> 00:17:23,109
Captain,
I'm Detective Inspector McMillan...

259
00:17:23,209 --> 00:17:24,410
Clear the area, thank you.

260
00:17:24,510 --> 00:17:27,713
Yes, but I was here when the thing...
The bus with... The tunnel thing...

261
00:17:27,813 --> 00:17:30,583
I've read the report.
Now clear the area!

262
00:17:30,683 --> 00:17:32,585
Pandovski, get these men
out of the zone.

263
00:17:32,685 --> 00:17:34,887
Yes, but there's somebody
on board that bus...

264
00:17:34,987 --> 00:17:36,923
-Just move back, sir.
-She's mine!

265
00:17:37,023 --> 00:17:38,624
-Just move back, sir.
-All right.

266
00:17:40,126 --> 00:17:41,627
Perimeter guard, stand ready.

267
00:17:41,727 --> 00:17:43,029
(GUNS COCKING)

268
00:17:44,063 --> 00:17:47,300
Stay alert. Any hostile activity,

269
00:17:48,901 --> 00:17:49,969
shoot to kill.

270
00:17:51,671 --> 00:17:53,973
-BARCLAY: Here we go!
-That's my boys!

271
00:17:54,073 --> 00:17:56,042
You see, we lay a flat surface
between the bus and the wormhole,

272
00:17:56,142 --> 00:17:57,944
like duckboards, and we reverse into it!

273
00:17:58,044 --> 00:18:00,079
Let some air out of the tyres,
just a little bit.

274
00:18:00,179 --> 00:18:02,348
Spreads the weight of the bus,
gives you more grip against the sand.

275
00:18:02,448 --> 00:18:04,684
-Oh, that's good!
-Holidays in the Kalahari.

276
00:18:04,784 --> 00:18:07,687
-Yeah, but those wheels go deep.
-Then start digging.

277
00:18:07,787 --> 00:18:09,989
-With what?
-With this.

278
00:18:16,662 --> 00:18:18,230
Got anything else in there?

279
00:18:18,331 --> 00:18:21,901
Try that. Might help with the seats.

280
00:18:21,968 --> 00:18:23,169
Thanks!

281
00:18:23,736 --> 00:18:25,605
ANGELA: I can't find the keys.

282
00:18:25,705 --> 00:18:28,074
Buses don't have keys.
There's a master switch.

283
00:18:28,174 --> 00:18:30,242
Then it's one button for start,
the other one for stop, yeah?

284
00:18:30,343 --> 00:18:32,511
Right. Hold on. Oh, I've got it.

285
00:18:33,045 --> 00:18:35,815
Here we go, hold tight, ding-ding!

286
00:18:36,349 --> 00:18:38,050
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

287
00:18:41,087 --> 00:18:43,189
Oh, that doesn't sound too good.

288
00:18:44,690 --> 00:18:45,891
Oh.

289
00:18:46,525 --> 00:18:50,563
Never mind losing half the top deck,
do you know what's worse? Sand.

290
00:18:51,764 --> 00:18:55,167
Tiny little grains of sand.
The engine's clogged up.

291
00:18:55,901 --> 00:18:57,503
Anyone know mechanics?

292
00:18:57,603 --> 00:19:00,606
Me, I did a two-week NVQ at the garage.

293
00:19:01,340 --> 00:19:02,742
-Never finished it, but...
-Off you go, then.

294
00:19:02,842 --> 00:19:05,077
Try stripping the air filter,
fast as you can.

295
00:19:05,177 --> 00:19:07,580
-I'll be back in two ticks.
-Wait a minute.

296
00:19:07,680 --> 00:19:11,817
You're the man with all the answers.
I'm not letting you out of my sight.

297
00:19:16,288 --> 00:19:18,190
(CHIRRUPING)

298
00:19:22,495 --> 00:19:24,230
Easier if you left that backpack behind.

299
00:19:24,330 --> 00:19:26,132
Where I go, it goes.

300
00:19:26,232 --> 00:19:28,701
A backpack, with a spade and an axe.

301
00:19:29,535 --> 00:19:33,773
Christina, who's going so far away
and yet scared by the sound of a siren.

302
00:19:33,873 --> 00:19:36,008
-Who are you?
-You can talk.

303
00:19:37,209 --> 00:19:39,945
Let's just say
we're two equal mysteries.

304
00:19:40,046 --> 00:19:41,147
We'd make quite a couple.

305
00:19:41,247 --> 00:19:44,083
We don't make any sort of couple,
thank you very much.

306
00:19:44,183 --> 00:19:46,318
Come on, then. Tell me.

307
00:19:46,419 --> 00:19:50,623
If Carmen's right, if that wormhole's
not an accident, then what is it?

308
00:19:50,723 --> 00:19:53,626
-Has someone done this on purpose?
-I don't know.

309
00:19:53,726 --> 00:19:54,927
But every single instinct of mine

310
00:19:55,027 --> 00:19:57,329
is telling me to get off this planet
right now.

311
00:19:57,430 --> 00:20:00,266
-And do you think we can?
-I live in hope.

312
00:20:00,366 --> 00:20:02,001
That must be nice.

313
00:20:04,804 --> 00:20:06,906
It's Christina de Souza.

314
00:20:07,006 --> 00:20:09,408
To be precise, Lady Christina de Souza.

315
00:20:09,508 --> 00:20:11,610
Oh, that's handy. 'Cause I'm a lord.

316
00:20:11,711 --> 00:20:13,746
Seriously? The Lord of where?

317
00:20:13,846 --> 00:20:16,048
It's quite a big estate.

318
00:20:16,148 --> 00:20:18,818
No, but there's something
more about you.

319
00:20:19,552 --> 00:20:23,322
That device you were carrying,
and the wormhole. Like you knew.

320
00:20:25,057 --> 00:20:28,227
And the way you stride
around this place, like...

321
00:20:29,929 --> 00:20:32,631
-Like?
-Like you're not quite...

322
00:20:34,667 --> 00:20:35,901
Anyway, come on!

323
00:20:36,001 --> 00:20:37,570
-Allons-y!
-0ui,

324
00:20:37,670 --> 00:20:39,238
mars pas s/ nous allons
vers urn cauchermar.

325
00:20:39,338 --> 00:20:42,308
DOCTOR: (LAUGHING)
We were made for each other!

326
00:20:43,008 --> 00:20:45,044
Ah, don't like the look of that.

327
00:20:45,144 --> 00:20:48,180
CHRISTINA: Storm clouds.
Must be hundreds of miles away.

328
00:20:48,280 --> 00:20:49,882
But getting closer.

329
00:20:49,982 --> 00:20:52,718
If that's a sandstorm,
we'll get ripped to shreds.

330
00:20:52,818 --> 00:20:55,821
It's a storm. Who said it's sand?

331
00:20:59,825 --> 00:21:01,827
Closer and closer and closer.

332
00:21:02,628 --> 00:21:04,130
Where is it?

333
00:21:04,230 --> 00:21:06,565
There, there, on the seat.

334
00:21:06,665 --> 00:21:08,634
You're hardly going to get a signal,
we're on another planet!

335
00:21:08,734 --> 00:21:10,402
Oh, just watch me.

336
00:21:10,503 --> 00:21:13,439
Right, now, bit of hush, thank you!

337
00:21:13,539 --> 00:21:16,142
I've got to remember the number,
a very important number.

338
00:21:16,242 --> 00:21:17,810
(PHONE RINGS)

339
00:21:17,910 --> 00:21:19,545
MAN: Hello, Pizza Geronimo.

340
00:21:19,645 --> 00:21:22,648
Then again! Ah! Seven-six not six-seven.

341
00:21:22,748 --> 00:21:24,150
(DIALLING)

342
00:21:24,250 --> 00:21:25,484
(PHONE RINGS)

343
00:21:26,085 --> 00:21:29,121
MALE VOICE.: This is the Unified
Intelligence Taskforce.

344
00:21:29,221 --> 00:21:32,324
Please select one of
the following four options.

345
00:21:32,424 --> 00:21:33,692
Oh, I hate these things!

346
00:21:33,793 --> 00:21:37,062
No, if you keep your finger pressed on
zero, you get through to a real person.

347
00:21:37,163 --> 00:21:39,365
- I saw it on Watchdog.
-Thank you, Angela.

348
00:21:39,465 --> 00:21:41,767
WOMAN: UNIT helpline,
which department would you like?

349
00:21:41,867 --> 00:21:43,702
Listen, it's the Doctor! It's me!

350
00:21:45,805 --> 00:21:48,207
Captain! Urgent call, ma'am,
relayed direct from HQ.

351
00:21:48,307 --> 00:21:51,377
-Who is it?
-It's him, ma'am. It's the Doctor.

352
00:21:54,346 --> 00:21:57,817
Doctor, this is Captain Erisa Magambo.

353
00:21:58,784 --> 00:22:02,021
Might I say, sir, it's an honour.

354
00:22:02,121 --> 00:22:03,856
Did you just salute?

355
00:22:05,658 --> 00:22:06,692
No.

356
00:22:06,792 --> 00:22:09,128
Erisa, it's about the bus.
HQ said you're at the tunnel, yeah?

357
00:22:09,228 --> 00:22:11,063
-And where are you?
-I'm on the bus.

358
00:22:11,163 --> 00:22:13,766
But apart from that, not a clue.

359
00:22:13,866 --> 00:22:17,570
Except it's very pretty
and pretty dangerous.

360
00:22:17,670 --> 00:22:21,640
A body came through here.
Have you sustained any more fatalities?

361
00:22:21,740 --> 00:22:24,410
No, and we're not going to.
But I'm stuck, I haven't got the TARDIS,

362
00:22:24,510 --> 00:22:26,011
and I need to analyse that wormhole.

363
00:22:26,111 --> 00:22:29,748
We have a scientific adviser on site,
Dr Malcolm Taylor.

364
00:22:30,783 --> 00:22:32,985
Just the man you need, he's a genius.

365
00:22:33,085 --> 00:22:35,821
DOCTOR: Oh, is he? We'll see about that.

366
00:22:36,622 --> 00:22:40,125
-Here's the Doctor.
-No, I'm all right now, thanks.

367
00:22:40,226 --> 00:22:42,428
It was just
a little bit of a sore throat.

368
00:22:42,528 --> 00:22:45,431
Although, I've got to be honest,
a cup of tea might be nice.

369
00:22:45,531 --> 00:22:47,366
It's The Doctor.

370
00:22:52,671 --> 00:22:56,709
Do you mean "The Doctor" Doctor?

371
00:22:56,809 --> 00:23:00,112
I know, we all want to meet him one day,

372
00:23:00,212 --> 00:23:01,580
but we all know
what that day will bring.

373
00:23:01,680 --> 00:23:03,549
DOCTOR: I can hear
everything you're saying.

374
00:23:03,649 --> 00:23:06,051
(EXCLAIMS INCREDULOUSLY)

375
00:23:09,655 --> 00:23:14,293
-Hello, Doctor. Oh, my goodness!
-Yes, I am. Hello, Malcolm!

376
00:23:14,360 --> 00:23:16,028
(CHUCKLES)

377
00:23:16,128 --> 00:23:18,397
The Doctor! Cor blimey!

378
00:23:18,497 --> 00:23:20,866
I can't believe
I'm actually speaking to you!

379
00:23:20,966 --> 00:23:23,569
-I mean, I've read all the files!
-Really?

380
00:23:23,669 --> 00:23:24,770
What was your favourite,
The Giant Robot?

381
00:23:24,870 --> 00:23:26,939
No, no, hold on,
let's sort out that wormhole.

382
00:23:27,039 --> 00:23:29,608
-Excuse me.
-On speakerphone, please.

383
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:33,646
I don't want anyone keeping secrets.

384
00:23:33,746 --> 00:23:35,047
Malcolm, something's not
making sense here.

385
00:23:35,147 --> 00:23:36,682
I've got a storm and a wormhole

386
00:23:36,782 --> 00:23:38,350
and I can't help thinking
there's a connection.

387
00:23:38,450 --> 00:23:41,353
I need a complete full-range analysis
of that wormhole, the whole thing.

388
00:23:41,453 --> 00:23:44,823
Well, I've probably got the wrong idea,
but I've wired up an integrator.

389
00:23:44,924 --> 00:23:46,625
I thought it could measure
the energy signature.

390
00:23:46,725 --> 00:23:48,160
No, no, no, that'll never work.
Just listen to me.

391
00:23:48,260 --> 00:23:49,762
It's quite extraordinary, though!

392
00:23:49,862 --> 00:23:53,332
I'm measuring an oscillation
of 15 Malcolms per second.

393
00:23:53,432 --> 00:23:55,167
-Fifteen what?
-Fifteen Malcolms.

394
00:23:55,267 --> 00:23:58,637
It's my own little term.
A wavelength parcel of 10 kilohertz

395
00:23:58,737 --> 00:24:01,941
operating in four dimensions
equals one Malcolm.

396
00:24:02,374 --> 00:24:06,278
You named a unit of measurement
after yourself?

397
00:24:06,378 --> 00:24:07,846
Well, it didn't do Mr Watt any harm.

398
00:24:07,947 --> 00:24:11,083
Furthermore, 100 Malcolms
equals a Bernard.

399
00:24:11,183 --> 00:24:12,451
Who's that, your dad?

400
00:24:12,551 --> 00:24:15,287
Don't be ridiculous, that's Quatermass.

401
00:24:15,387 --> 00:24:16,755
Right.

402
00:24:16,855 --> 00:24:19,792
Fine. But before I die of old age,

403
00:24:19,892 --> 00:24:22,828
which in my case would be quite an
achievement, so congratulations on that,

404
00:24:22,928 --> 00:24:24,430
is there anyone else I can talk to?

405
00:24:24,530 --> 00:24:26,365
No, no, no, no, but listen.

406
00:24:26,465 --> 00:24:30,869
I set the scanner to register what
it can't detect and inverted the image.

407
00:24:31,737 --> 00:24:33,806
-You did what?
-Is that wrong?

408
00:24:33,906 --> 00:24:37,009
No, Malcolm, that's brilliant! So you
can actually measure the wormhole.

409
00:24:37,109 --> 00:24:39,445
Okay, I admit, that is genius.

410
00:24:40,112 --> 00:24:42,481
-The Doctor called me a genius.
-I know, I heard.

411
00:24:42,581 --> 00:24:44,316
Now, run a capacity scan.
I need a full report.

412
00:24:44,416 --> 00:24:47,519
Call me back when you've done it.
And, Malcolm?

413
00:24:48,854 --> 00:24:51,890
-You're my new best friend!
-And you're mine, too, sir.

414
00:24:52,458 --> 00:24:55,828
-Barclay, I'm holding on to this.
-Then you'd better bring it back!

415
00:24:58,097 --> 00:25:01,133
You're, you're mine...
He's gone. He's gone.

416
00:25:05,671 --> 00:25:07,172
(CHIRRUPING)

417
00:25:09,408 --> 00:25:13,145
DOCTOR: Send this back to Earth,
see if Malcolm can analyse the storm.

418
00:25:13,245 --> 00:25:16,548
There's something in those clouds.
Something shining, look.

419
00:25:16,648 --> 00:25:17,816
(CAMERA CLICKS)

420
00:25:18,450 --> 00:25:20,386
DOCTOR: Like metal.

421
00:25:20,486 --> 00:25:22,955
CHRISTINA: Why would there
be metal in a storm?

422
00:25:23,055 --> 00:25:27,559
So fast and strong, they ride the storm.

423
00:25:27,693 --> 00:25:29,361
(VOICES WHISPERING)

424
00:25:29,661 --> 00:25:31,530
They are the storm.

425
00:25:32,631 --> 00:25:34,099
What are they?

426
00:25:36,301 --> 00:25:37,469
They devour.

427
00:25:37,569 --> 00:25:38,971
(CHIRRUPING)

428
00:25:39,071 --> 00:25:41,940
-Did you hear something?
-Hold on. Busy.

429
00:25:42,041 --> 00:25:44,443
There was a noise, like a sort of...

430
00:25:44,543 --> 00:25:45,611
(GRUNTING)

431
00:25:45,711 --> 00:25:46,979
(CHIRRUPING)

432
00:25:48,280 --> 00:25:49,581
Doctor...

433
00:25:52,051 --> 00:25:53,352
There's something new.

434
00:25:53,452 --> 00:25:55,120
(CHIRRUPING)

435
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:56,388
(GRUNTING)

436
00:25:56,488 --> 00:25:58,157
(MOUTHING)

437
00:25:58,257 --> 00:26:01,393
That's "wait".
I shout "wait", people usually wait.

438
00:26:01,493 --> 00:26:03,362
-You speak the language?
-Every language.

439
00:26:03,462 --> 00:26:04,963
(CHIRRUPING)

440
00:26:05,064 --> 00:26:06,165
(GRUNTING)

441
00:26:06,265 --> 00:26:07,800
(CHIRRUPING)

442
00:26:07,900 --> 00:26:09,635
That's begging for mercy.

443
00:26:09,735 --> 00:26:11,070
(CHIRRUPING)

444
00:26:11,170 --> 00:26:13,605
-That means "move".
-Oh, you're learning.

445
00:26:19,812 --> 00:26:22,081
CHRISTINA: These fly things,
they must be responsible.

446
00:26:22,181 --> 00:26:23,248
They brought us here.

447
00:26:23,348 --> 00:26:25,384
DOCTOR: No, no, no, no!
Look at the ship, it's a wreck.

448
00:26:25,484 --> 00:26:27,519
They crashed just like us.

449
00:26:29,254 --> 00:26:31,890
CHRISTINA:
Oh, but this place is freezing!

450
00:26:31,990 --> 00:26:34,726
DOCTOR: Hmm.
The hull's made of Photafine steel.

451
00:26:37,496 --> 00:26:38,931
Turns cold when it's hot.

452
00:26:39,031 --> 00:26:41,834
Boiling desert outside,
freezing ship inside.

453
00:26:41,934 --> 00:26:44,203
Since I met you, Christina,
we've been through all the extremes.

454
00:26:44,303 --> 00:26:46,805
That's how I like things. Extreme.

455
00:26:48,107 --> 00:26:49,641
(HISSING)

456
00:26:49,741 --> 00:26:51,009
(CHIRRUPING)

457
00:26:51,110 --> 00:26:53,545
Oh, this is beautiful.

458
00:26:53,645 --> 00:26:57,516
Intact, it must've been magnificent.
A proper, streamlined deep-spacer!

459
00:26:57,616 --> 00:26:59,718
Oh, I'll remember that
as I'm being slowly tortured.

460
00:26:59,818 --> 00:27:04,056
At least I'm bleeding on the floor
of a really well-designed spaceship.

461
00:27:07,926 --> 00:27:10,963
(CHIRRUPING)

462
00:27:14,967 --> 00:27:17,236
Oh, right, good, yes. Hello!

463
00:27:17,336 --> 00:27:20,005
That's a telepathic translator.
He can understand us.

464
00:27:20,105 --> 00:27:21,707
(WARBLING)

465
00:27:22,908 --> 00:27:25,010
Still sounds like gibberish to me.

466
00:27:25,110 --> 00:27:27,146
That's what I said,
he can understand us.

467
00:27:27,246 --> 00:27:29,314
Doesn't work the other way round.

468
00:27:29,414 --> 00:27:31,116
(CHIRRUPING)

469
00:27:31,216 --> 00:27:34,319
"You will suffer for your crimes."”

470
00:27:36,288 --> 00:27:40,792
EX cetera. "You have committed
an act of violence

471
00:27:40,893 --> 00:27:44,429
"against the Tritovore race.”
Tritovores, they're called Tritovores.

472
00:27:44,530 --> 00:27:48,534
"You came here in the 200
to destroy us."

473
00:27:48,967 --> 00:27:50,636
Sorry, what's the 2007

474
00:27:50,736 --> 00:27:53,739
It's the bus, number 200,
they mean the bus.

475
00:27:53,839 --> 00:27:56,475
Oh, no, look, I think you're making
the same mistake Christina did.

476
00:27:56,575 --> 00:27:58,410
I'm the Doctor, by the way,
and this is Christina,

477
00:27:58,510 --> 00:28:01,380
the honourable Lady Christina,
at least I hope she's honourable.

478
00:28:01,480 --> 00:28:04,850
But we got pulled through that wormhole.
The 200 doesn't look like that normally.

479
00:28:04,950 --> 00:28:06,718
It's broken, just the same as you.

480
00:28:06,818 --> 00:28:08,820
(CHIRRUPING)

481
00:28:13,091 --> 00:28:15,794
-What are they doing?
-They believe me!

482
00:28:15,894 --> 00:28:19,464
-What, simple as that?
-I've got a very honest face.

483
00:28:19,565 --> 00:28:22,634
And the translator says
I'm telling the truth.

484
00:28:22,734 --> 00:28:24,503
Plus, the face.

485
00:28:24,603 --> 00:28:26,638
Right! So, first things first,

486
00:28:26,738 --> 00:28:30,542
there's a very strange storm heading
our way, can you send out a probe?

487
00:28:30,642 --> 00:28:32,177
(CHIRRUPING)

488
00:28:32,611 --> 00:28:35,047
Oh. They've lost power.

489
00:28:36,815 --> 00:28:40,352
Hmm. The crash knocked the mainline
crystallography out of synch,

490
00:28:40,452 --> 00:28:43,789
but if I can jiggle it back...

491
00:28:43,855 --> 00:28:44,957
(GRUNTING)

492
00:28:45,057 --> 00:28:46,291
(MACHINE WHIRRING)

493
00:28:46,391 --> 00:28:47,526
I thank you!

494
00:28:47,626 --> 00:28:48,994
(CHIRRUPING)

495
00:28:49,094 --> 00:28:51,863
Yes, I am! Frequently.

496
00:28:51,964 --> 00:28:55,167
Okey-doke, let's launch that probe.

497
00:29:01,406 --> 00:29:05,110
The Scorpion Nebula.
We're on the other side of the universe.

498
00:29:05,210 --> 00:29:07,379
Just what you wanted, so far away.

499
00:29:09,982 --> 00:29:12,150
The planet of San Helios.

500
00:29:13,018 --> 00:29:14,620
And that's us.

501
00:29:15,087 --> 00:29:16,788
We're on another world.

502
00:29:16,888 --> 00:29:19,992
-We have been for quite a while.
-I know, but seeing it like that...

503
00:29:20,092 --> 00:29:22,594
-It's good, isn't it?
-Wonderful.

504
00:29:22,694 --> 00:29:24,062
(CHIRRUPING RAPIDLY)

505
00:29:24,129 --> 00:29:25,664
(GRUNTING)

506
00:29:25,764 --> 00:29:28,500
The Tritovores were going to trade
with San Helios.

507
00:29:29,801 --> 00:29:31,970
Population of 100 billion.

508
00:29:32,070 --> 00:29:34,239
Plenty of waste matter
for them to absorb.

509
00:29:34,339 --> 00:29:35,841
By waste matter, you mean...

510
00:29:35,941 --> 00:29:38,644
They feed off what others leave behind.

511
00:29:39,044 --> 00:29:40,479
From their...

512
00:29:40,946 --> 00:29:41,980
Behind,

513
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:44,549
if you see what I mean.
It's perfectly natural. They are flies.

514
00:29:44,650 --> 00:29:46,985
Charming.
Just remind me never to kiss them.

515
00:29:47,085 --> 00:29:48,920
(CHIRRUPING)

516
00:29:50,689 --> 00:29:54,092
DOCTOR: San Helios City.
CHRISTINA: That's amazing.

517
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:59,331
But you've seen this sort of thing
before, haven't you?

518
00:29:59,431 --> 00:30:01,199
DOCTOR: Thousands of times.

519
00:30:01,300 --> 00:30:04,102
That Lordship of yours.
The Lord of where, exactly?

520
00:30:04,202 --> 00:30:09,074
Of Time. I come from a race of people
called Time Lords.

521
00:30:09,174 --> 00:30:11,209
-You're an alien?
-Yeah.

522
00:30:11,310 --> 00:30:13,578
But you don't have to kiss me either.

523
00:30:13,679 --> 00:30:16,048
-You look human.
-You look Time Lord.

524
00:30:19,451 --> 00:30:21,820
-Anyway...
-So, if that's San Helios,

525
00:30:21,920 --> 00:30:25,390
all we need to do is find that city.
They can help us!

526
00:30:25,490 --> 00:30:27,459
I don't think it's that simple.

527
00:30:33,031 --> 00:30:35,400
We're in the city right now.

528
00:30:36,468 --> 00:30:38,370
CHRISTINA: But it's sand.

529
00:30:38,704 --> 00:30:41,006
That first image, the temples
and things, what's that, then?

530
00:30:41,106 --> 00:30:42,274
Ancient history?

531
00:30:42,374 --> 00:30:44,710
(CHIRRUPING)

532
00:30:45,310 --> 00:30:49,648
-The image was taken last year.
-It became a desert in one year?

533
00:30:51,216 --> 00:30:53,819
I said there was something in the sand.

534
00:30:57,055 --> 00:31:02,728
The city, the oceans,
the mountains, the wildlife,

535
00:31:03,295 --> 00:31:06,064
and 100 billion people, turned to sand.

536
00:31:07,065 --> 00:31:09,468
All those voices in Carmen's head.

537
00:31:10,769 --> 00:31:12,704
She's hearing them die.

538
00:31:13,138 --> 00:31:15,507
But I've got sand in my hair.

539
00:31:15,607 --> 00:31:18,276
That's dead people!
Oh, that's disgusting! Oh!

540
00:31:18,377 --> 00:31:20,679
Something destroyed
the whole of San Helios.

541
00:31:20,779 --> 00:31:22,247
Yes, but in my hair!

542
00:31:22,347 --> 00:31:23,548
(MOBILE PHONE RINGING)

543
00:31:25,417 --> 00:31:27,119
DOCTOR: Malcolm! Tell me the bad news!/

544
00:31:27,219 --> 00:31:28,854
Oh, you are clever!

545
00:31:30,021 --> 00:31:31,490
It is bad news!

546
00:31:32,190 --> 00:31:35,227
It's the wormhole, Doctor,
it's getting bigger!

547
00:31:35,327 --> 00:31:39,831
We've gone way past 100 Bernards,
I haven't invented a name for that.

548
00:31:39,931 --> 00:31:41,166
How can it get bigger by itself?

549
00:31:41,266 --> 00:31:42,567
(BEEPING)

550
00:31:42,667 --> 00:31:46,605
That's why I'm phoning!
You'll work it out, if I know you, sir!

551
00:31:47,038 --> 00:31:50,842
Doctor, we estimate the circumference
of your invisible wormhole

552
00:31:50,942 --> 00:31:53,945
is now four miles, heading outwards.

553
00:31:54,045 --> 00:31:56,248
I've grounded all flights above London,

554
00:31:56,348 --> 00:31:57,983
we can't risk anyone else
falling through.

555
00:31:58,083 --> 00:32:01,119
-Good work, both of you.
-But I have to know.

556
00:32:01,219 --> 00:32:03,054
Does that wormhole constitute
a danger to this planet?

557
00:32:03,121 --> 00:32:04,289
(BEEPING)

558
00:32:04,389 --> 00:32:06,024
Oh, sorry, call waiting. Gotta go!

559
00:32:06,358 --> 00:32:09,161
-Call waiting?
-He's a devil, that one!

560
00:32:10,629 --> 00:32:13,064
-Yeah?
-Doctor, it's Nathan.

561
00:32:13,665 --> 00:32:15,233
We got those duck board
things down, but...

562
00:32:15,333 --> 00:32:18,003
-It's my fault.
-No, it's not, don't say that.

563
00:32:18,103 --> 00:32:21,907
-Why, what's happened?
-We kept on turning the engine, but...

564
00:32:23,208 --> 00:32:25,911
We're out of petrol. Used it all up.

565
00:32:26,878 --> 00:32:31,149
Even if we can get those wheels out,
this bus is never going to move.

566
00:32:33,051 --> 00:32:35,787
What is it, what's wrong?
Doctor, tell me.

567
00:32:36,721 --> 00:32:40,258
You promised you'd get us home. Doctor?

568
00:32:41,026 --> 00:32:43,695
-Are you still there?
-Doctor, tell me, what did he say?

569
00:32:43,762 --> 00:32:45,063
(BEEPING)

570
00:32:45,163 --> 00:32:46,465
(CHIRRUPING)

571
00:32:49,267 --> 00:32:51,236
It's the probe. It's reached the storm.

572
00:32:51,336 --> 00:32:53,004
(CHIRRUPING)

573
00:32:53,104 --> 00:32:56,041
-And what's he saying?
-It's not a storm.

574
00:32:56,842 --> 00:32:58,510
(SQUEALING)

575
00:33:04,616 --> 00:33:05,817
It's a swarm.

576
00:33:06,785 --> 00:33:09,321
-Millions of them.
-DOCTOR: Billions.

577
00:33:18,897 --> 00:33:21,533
Ah! We've lost the probe.
I think it got eaten.

578
00:33:21,633 --> 00:33:24,302
-Everything on this planet gets eaten.
-How far away is that swarm?

579
00:33:24,402 --> 00:33:27,205
Hundred miles. At that speed,
it'll be here in 20 minutes.

580
00:33:27,305 --> 00:33:29,140
(CHIRRUPING)

581
00:33:29,241 --> 00:33:31,743
No, no, they're not just coming for us.
They want the wormhole.

582
00:33:31,843 --> 00:33:34,646
-They're heading for Earth!
-Show the analysis!

583
00:33:37,015 --> 00:33:38,416
Incredible!

584
00:33:39,084 --> 00:33:41,353
They swarm out of a wormhole,
strip the planet bare,

585
00:33:41,453 --> 00:33:45,790
then move on to the next world,
start the life cycle all over again.

586
00:33:45,891 --> 00:33:48,793
-So, they make the wormholes?
-They must do.

587
00:33:48,894 --> 00:33:51,830
But how? They don't exactly
look like technicians.

588
00:33:51,930 --> 00:33:55,367
And if the wormhole belongs to them,
why are they 100 miles away?

589
00:33:55,467 --> 00:33:59,704
Because they need to be?
No, that's bonkers. Hang on.

590
00:34:02,107 --> 00:34:05,043
Yes! Oh, do you see?

591
00:34:05,143 --> 00:34:07,612
Billions of them flying in formation,
all the way around the planet,

592
00:34:07,712 --> 00:34:10,682
round and round and round,
faster and faster and faster,

593
00:34:10,782 --> 00:34:13,585
till they generate a rupture in space!

594
00:34:13,685 --> 00:34:16,187
The speed of them, and the numbers,
and the size,

595
00:34:16,288 --> 00:34:18,290
all of that rips the wormhole
into existence!

596
00:34:18,390 --> 00:34:20,559
-And the wormhole's getting bigger.
-Because they're getting closer!

597
00:34:20,659 --> 00:34:21,726
But how do they get through?

598
00:34:21,826 --> 00:34:23,395
'Cause that wormhole's a killer,
we've seen it.

599
00:34:23,495 --> 00:34:26,932
-No, no, look. See the exoskeleton?
-Metal.

600
00:34:27,732 --> 00:34:29,434
They've got bones of metal.

601
00:34:29,534 --> 00:34:32,671
They eat metal and extrude it
into the exoskeleton.

602
00:34:32,771 --> 00:34:36,808
So their velocity makes the wormhole,
then their body makes it safe.

603
00:34:37,976 --> 00:34:39,711
Perfect design.

604
00:34:39,811 --> 00:34:43,214
Those things are going to turn
the entire Earth into a desert.

605
00:34:43,315 --> 00:34:45,684
So why exactly are you smiling?

606
00:34:47,786 --> 00:34:50,722
-Worse it gets, the more I love it!
-Me, too.

607
00:34:52,123 --> 00:34:53,925
(SQUEALING)

608
00:34:57,429 --> 00:34:58,930
(RUMBLING)

609
00:34:59,731 --> 00:35:03,735
-Sounds like a storm.
-If it rains, we've got water.

610
00:35:03,835 --> 00:35:07,272
No water. All of it, dust.

611
00:35:07,539 --> 00:35:08,807
(VOICES WHISPERING)

612
00:35:08,907 --> 00:35:13,745
-But the girl...
-Don't now, sweetheart. What girl?

613
00:35:14,379 --> 00:35:17,015
The girl, she will fly.

614
00:35:17,816 --> 00:35:20,685
The thing is, Doctor,
you're missing the obvious.

615
00:35:20,785 --> 00:35:23,488
We came here through the wormhole, yes?

616
00:35:23,588 --> 00:35:27,525
But our Tritovore friends didn't.
They came here to trade with San Helios.

617
00:35:27,626 --> 00:35:31,096
Therefore, the question is,
why did they crash?

618
00:35:31,196 --> 00:35:37,035
Ah. Good question! What a team!
Like she said, why did you crash?

619
00:35:37,702 --> 00:35:39,004
Oh, yes!

620
00:35:40,305 --> 00:35:42,807
Gravity Well. Look, goes all the way
down to the engine.

621
00:35:42,907 --> 00:35:44,109
So what happened?

622
00:35:44,209 --> 00:35:45,710
(CHIRRUPING)

623
00:35:46,411 --> 00:35:48,747
He says the drive system stalled.

624
00:35:49,514 --> 00:35:51,983
Ten miles up, they fell out of the sky.
But what caused that?

625
00:35:52,083 --> 00:35:53,118
(CHIRRUPING)

626
00:35:53,218 --> 00:35:55,587
-Which means, "No idea."
-Yeah.

627
00:35:56,187 --> 00:35:58,556
But wait a minute, that's
a crystal nucleus down there, yes?

628
00:35:58,623 --> 00:35:59,691
(GRUNTS)

629
00:35:59,791 --> 00:36:03,328
And it looks like it survived the crash.
If the crystal's intact...

630
00:36:03,428 --> 00:36:06,798
Oh, yes, that's better than diesel!

631
00:36:06,898 --> 00:36:08,867
What, you can use the crystal
to move the bus?

632
00:36:08,933 --> 00:36:10,602
I think so.

633
00:36:10,702 --> 00:36:12,504
The spaceship's a write-off,
but the 200's small enough.

634
00:36:12,604 --> 00:36:14,205
How does a crystal drive a bus?

635
00:36:14,305 --> 00:36:17,809
In a super-clever, outer-spacey way.
Just trust me.

636
00:36:17,909 --> 00:36:20,045
There's the crystal.
It's fallen to the bottom of the well.

637
00:36:20,145 --> 00:36:21,680
Have you got access shafts?

638
00:36:21,780 --> 00:36:22,914
(CHIRRUPING)

639
00:36:23,014 --> 00:36:25,316
All frozen. Well, maybe I can open them!

640
00:36:25,417 --> 00:36:28,687
Ah! Internal comms, put that on!

641
00:36:28,787 --> 00:36:32,991
You stay here! Keep an eye on the shaft!
Tell me if anything happens!

642
00:36:42,634 --> 00:36:45,737
If I can use that sunlight
to start the automatic maintenance.

643
00:36:45,837 --> 00:36:46,905
Christina?

644
00:36:47,005 --> 00:36:50,608
(GRUNTS) If you see a panel
opening in that shaft, let me know.

645
00:36:50,709 --> 00:36:52,977
-Nothing yet.
-Anything now?

646
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:55,814
-Afraid not.
-Any sign of movement?

647
00:36:55,914 --> 00:36:56,948
Nope.

648
00:36:58,249 --> 00:37:00,151
-How's that?
-Nothing.

649
00:37:01,086 --> 00:37:04,155
-Any result?
-Not a Dickie bird.

650
00:37:05,623 --> 00:37:09,928
So let me get this right.
You need that crystal?

651
00:37:12,430 --> 00:37:14,833
-Then consider it done.
-Why, what do you mean?

652
00:37:16,334 --> 00:37:17,535
Christina?

653
00:37:19,304 --> 00:37:20,705
Christina!

654
00:37:21,406 --> 00:37:23,742
The aristocracy survives for a reason.

655
00:37:27,178 --> 00:37:28,813
We're ready for anything.

656
00:37:31,382 --> 00:37:32,550
No!

657
00:37:39,290 --> 00:37:42,393
Come on! Come on!
Come on, come on, come on!

658
00:37:43,995 --> 00:37:47,599
-That's better.
-I decide when I stop, thank you.

659
00:37:47,699 --> 00:37:50,034
You were about to hit
the security grid. Look!

660
00:37:50,969 --> 00:37:54,105
Excellent. So what do I do?

661
00:37:54,606 --> 00:37:56,508
DOCTOR: Try the big red button.

662
00:37:58,076 --> 00:38:01,479
-Well done!
-Now come back up! I can do that.

663
00:38:01,579 --> 00:38:04,315
-Oh, don't you wish.
-Slowly!

664
00:38:05,784 --> 00:38:07,452
CHRISTINA: Yes, sir.

665
00:38:09,654 --> 00:38:13,992
Quite the mystery, aren't you?
Lady Christina de Souza.

666
00:38:15,193 --> 00:38:18,930
-Carrying a winch in her bag.
-No stranger than you, spaceman.

667
00:38:19,864 --> 00:38:21,833
I had this friend once.

668
00:38:22,500 --> 00:38:25,270
-She called me spaceman.
-And was she right?

669
00:38:25,370 --> 00:38:27,372
Do you zoom about the place in a rocket?

670
00:38:27,472 --> 00:38:29,774
Well, a little, blue box.

671
00:38:31,709 --> 00:38:33,745
Travels in more than space.

672
00:38:35,313 --> 00:38:37,816
It can journey through time, Christina.

673
00:38:38,316 --> 00:38:41,786
Oh, the places I've been. World War I.

674
00:38:42,787 --> 00:38:45,557
Creation of the universe,
end of the universe,

675
00:38:45,857 --> 00:38:47,992
the war between China and Japan.

676
00:38:48,860 --> 00:38:54,199
And the court of King Athelstan
in 924 AD.

677
00:38:54,833 --> 00:38:59,170
But I don't remember you being there.
So what are you doing with this?

678
00:38:59,637 --> 00:39:03,775
Excuse me. A gentleman never
goes through a lady's possessions.

679
00:39:03,875 --> 00:39:05,276
(CHIRRUPING)

680
00:39:06,311 --> 00:39:07,912
It's the Cup of Athelstan.

681
00:39:08,012 --> 00:39:10,748
Given to the first king of Britain
as a coronation gift from Hywel,

682
00:39:10,849 --> 00:39:12,717
King of the Welsh.

683
00:39:12,817 --> 00:39:15,854
But it's been held in the
International Gallery for 200 years,

684
00:39:15,954 --> 00:39:19,924
which makes you, Lady Christina,
a thief.

685
00:39:20,024 --> 00:39:21,893
I like to think I liberated it.

686
00:39:21,993 --> 00:39:24,596
-Don't tell me you need the money.
-Daddy lost everything.

687
00:39:24,696 --> 00:39:26,931
Invested his fortune
in the Icelandic banks.

688
00:39:27,031 --> 00:39:30,735
No, no, no, if you're short of cash,
you rob a bank.

689
00:39:30,835 --> 00:39:35,173
-Stealing this, that's a lifestyle.
-I take it you disapprove?

690
00:39:35,473 --> 00:39:37,475
Absolutely.

691
00:39:37,742 --> 00:39:40,979
Except, that little, blue box.

692
00:39:42,614 --> 00:39:47,585
-I stole it. From my own people.
-Good boy.

693
00:39:47,952 --> 00:39:50,255
You were right. We're quite a team.

694
00:39:50,955 --> 00:39:52,290
(SCREECHING)

695
00:39:53,658 --> 00:39:54,726
What the blazes was that?

696
00:39:54,826 --> 00:39:56,327
We never did find out
why the ship crashed.

697
00:39:56,427 --> 00:39:57,795
Christina, I think you should
come back up.

698
00:39:57,896 --> 00:40:00,198
Too late. I can see it.

699
00:40:00,298 --> 00:40:02,967
Careful. Slowly.
Have you got an open-vent system?

700
00:40:03,067 --> 00:40:04,936
-I thought so.
-What does that mean?

701
00:40:05,036 --> 00:40:06,871
It's like when birds fly
into the engines of an aircraft.

702
00:40:06,938 --> 00:40:08,773
(GRUNTING)

703
00:40:10,408 --> 00:40:12,277
-One of the creatures.
-Got trapped in the vents.

704
00:40:12,377 --> 00:40:14,012
Caused the crash. Christina, get out.

705
00:40:14,112 --> 00:40:17,081
It's not moving. I think it's injured.

706
00:40:17,181 --> 00:40:18,750
No, it's dormant
because it's so cold down there.

707
00:40:18,850 --> 00:40:20,752
But your body heat
is raising the temperature.

708
00:40:20,852 --> 00:40:23,588
I tend to have that effect.
Almost there.

709
00:40:24,455 --> 00:40:27,659
Not just the crystal.
I need the whole bed, the plate thing.

710
00:40:33,665 --> 00:40:36,034
-CHRISTINA: I've got it!
-Come on! Come on!

711
00:40:41,339 --> 00:40:43,308
Come on! Come on! Come on! Come on!

712
00:40:47,946 --> 00:40:49,747
It's gonna eat its way up!

713
00:40:51,182 --> 00:40:52,951
(SQUEALING)

714
00:40:54,319 --> 00:40:55,753
Ooh! She's good!

715
00:40:58,156 --> 00:40:59,657
-That's it! That's it! That's it!
-Ooh!

716
00:40:59,757 --> 00:41:02,193
I've got you. I've got you.

717
00:41:02,260 --> 00:41:03,494
(GRUNTING)

718
00:41:03,594 --> 00:41:04,629
-Isn't she just?
-Yeah.

719
00:41:10,201 --> 00:41:11,469
Commander! Mission complete!

720
00:41:11,569 --> 00:41:14,572
Now we've got to get back to the 200,
all of us.

721
00:41:14,672 --> 00:41:16,074
Oh, don't be so daft.

722
00:41:16,174 --> 00:41:18,609
A captain can leave his ship
if there's a bus standing by.

723
00:41:18,710 --> 00:41:19,911
(RUMBLING)

724
00:41:20,011 --> 00:41:22,780
What the hell was that?
Is this place safe?

725
00:41:24,282 --> 00:41:26,384
It's the creature. It's not dead.

726
00:41:26,818 --> 00:41:28,553
(CHIRRUPING)

727
00:41:28,653 --> 00:41:31,789
Maybe you didn't hit just one of them.
If you hit a swarm...

728
00:41:31,889 --> 00:41:33,291
Do you mean, if there's more on board?

729
00:41:33,391 --> 00:41:35,293
This ship's built inside a metal sleeve.

730
00:41:35,393 --> 00:41:37,428
They can move through
the infrastructure all around us.

731
00:41:37,495 --> 00:41:38,796
(THUDDING)

732
00:41:38,896 --> 00:41:39,964
And those things wake up hungry.

733
00:41:40,064 --> 00:41:41,599
Commander, you've got to come with us,
right now!

734
00:41:41,699 --> 00:41:43,334
You can come back to Earth,
we'll find you a home!

735
00:41:43,434 --> 00:41:45,870
And that's the word of a lady! Come on!

736
00:41:46,871 --> 00:41:47,972
(CRASHING)

737
00:41:48,072 --> 00:41:49,574
(SCREAMING)

738
00:41:50,675 --> 00:41:52,110
(SQUEALING)

739
00:41:54,278 --> 00:41:55,580
(GRUNTING)

740
00:41:56,581 --> 00:41:57,815
No, don't!

741
00:42:03,021 --> 00:42:04,822
There's nothing we can do. Run!

742
00:42:19,237 --> 00:42:20,738
What sort of storm is that?

743
00:42:27,745 --> 00:42:32,383
Run, run, run, run, run, run, run!

744
00:42:32,984 --> 00:42:34,419
(MOBILE PHONE RINGING)

745
00:42:38,156 --> 00:42:40,691
-Ah, Doctor.
-Not now, Malcolm!

746
00:42:43,061 --> 00:42:45,696
Fair do's. He's a busy man.

747
00:42:57,842 --> 00:43:00,211
At last! Where've you been?

748
00:43:00,311 --> 00:43:02,513
Get inside, get them sitting down!

749
00:43:02,613 --> 00:43:04,182
Now then, let's have a look.

750
00:43:04,282 --> 00:43:06,517
-So what does that crystal do?
-Oh, nothing, don't need the crystal.

751
00:43:06,617 --> 00:43:09,587
-I risked my life for that!
-No, you risked your life for these.

752
00:43:09,654 --> 00:43:10,855
The clamps!

753
00:43:12,223 --> 00:43:13,558
One there!

754
00:43:15,460 --> 00:43:16,594
One there.

755
00:43:19,564 --> 00:43:22,767
One there! And one there!

756
00:43:22,867 --> 00:43:24,836
CHRISTINA: But what are the clamps for,
do they turn the wheels?

757
00:43:24,936 --> 00:43:26,237
Something like that.
Just need to fix this.

758
00:43:26,337 --> 00:43:29,440
-Have you got a hammer in that bag?
-Funnily enough.

759
00:43:30,942 --> 00:43:32,477
Now press redial!

760
00:43:35,146 --> 00:43:37,448
-Malcolm! It's me!
-I'm ready!

761
00:43:37,548 --> 00:43:39,884
-Ready for what?
-I don't know! You tell me!

762
00:43:39,984 --> 00:43:42,420
I'm gonna try to get back, but there
might be something following us.

763
00:43:42,520 --> 00:43:44,322
You need to find a way
to close the wormhole.

764
00:43:44,422 --> 00:43:45,890
Would that be
a compressed burst of feedback

765
00:43:45,990 --> 00:43:50,161
-on a counter-oscillation, perchance?
-Oh, Malcolm! You're brilliant!

766
00:43:50,261 --> 00:43:52,597
Coming from you, sir,
that means the world!

767
00:43:52,697 --> 00:43:54,765
MAGAMBO: Doctor, what sort of something?

768
00:43:54,866 --> 00:43:57,568
That wormhole is now measuring
10 miles and growing,

769
00:43:57,668 --> 00:43:59,570
I need to know
the exact nature of the threat.

770
00:43:59,670 --> 00:44:01,339
Sorry, gotta go!

771
00:44:02,673 --> 00:44:06,611
All troops, mobilise and stand ready!
Possible Code Red, unknown!

772
00:44:06,711 --> 00:44:10,214
-Understood. Code Red! Repeat, Code Red!
-SOLDIER: Position!

773
00:44:10,348 --> 00:44:11,916
(MEN SHOUTING)

774
00:44:23,694 --> 00:44:25,096
(CRACKLING)

775
00:44:26,464 --> 00:44:29,367
Ah, it's not compatible!
Bus, spaceship, spaceship, bus.

776
00:44:29,467 --> 00:44:30,801
I need to weld the two systems together.

777
00:44:30,902 --> 00:44:33,804
-And how do you do that?
-I need something non-corrosive,

778
00:44:33,905 --> 00:44:37,475
something malleable,
something ductile, something...

779
00:44:38,776 --> 00:44:41,345
-Gold.
-Oh, no, you don't.

780
00:44:41,445 --> 00:44:44,215
-Christina, what is it worth now?
-Hey! Use this!

781
00:44:44,315 --> 00:44:46,918
-I said gold!
-It is gold!

782
00:44:47,018 --> 00:44:49,020
Oh, they saw you coming. Christina!

783
00:45:04,835 --> 00:45:08,506
It's over 1,000 years old.
Worth £18 million.

784
00:45:09,340 --> 00:45:12,310
-Promise me you'll be careful.
-I promise.

785
00:45:20,351 --> 00:45:21,619
I hate you.

786
00:45:24,322 --> 00:45:25,489
(BEEPING)

787
00:45:25,590 --> 00:45:29,660
Done it! Transmit that
and the wormhole should close.

788
00:45:30,828 --> 00:45:32,096
Then do it.

789
00:45:32,763 --> 00:45:34,932
Well, after the Doctor's
come through, obviously.

790
00:45:35,032 --> 00:45:37,201
I'm sorry. Believe me.

791
00:45:38,035 --> 00:45:40,805
That wormhole
constitutes a major threat,

792
00:45:40,905 --> 00:45:44,742
and I have a duty to every man,
woman and child on this planet.

793
00:45:45,276 --> 00:45:48,546
-It's got to be closed immediately.
-No, no, no.

794
00:45:48,646 --> 00:45:52,083
-That's an order.
-No, no, no, no.

795
00:45:52,183 --> 00:45:54,986
No, we can't just abandon him!
He's the Doctor!

796
00:45:55,086 --> 00:46:00,658
How many times has he saved our lives?
I won't let you, ma"am. I simply won't!

797
00:46:04,028 --> 00:46:05,196
(GUN COCKING)

798
00:46:06,564 --> 00:46:08,199
Right now, soldier.

799
00:46:09,166 --> 00:46:11,736
This is your driver speaking.
Hold on tight.

800
00:46:11,836 --> 00:46:13,971
-What for, what's he doing?
-Do as he says!

801
00:46:14,071 --> 00:46:15,106
(ENGINE CRANKING)

802
00:46:15,206 --> 00:46:17,742
-What are you doing?
-Come on! That's it.

803
00:46:18,509 --> 00:46:21,579
You can do it, you beauty!
One last trip!

804
00:46:21,679 --> 00:46:23,180
(ENGINE POWERING UP)

805
00:46:23,281 --> 00:46:25,016
(RATTLING)

806
00:46:34,458 --> 00:46:36,394
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

807
00:46:40,431 --> 00:46:42,667
Oh! You are so kidding me!

808
00:46:47,238 --> 00:46:49,807
-We're flying! It's flying!
-Yes!

809
00:46:52,376 --> 00:46:53,878
He's flying the bus!

810
00:46:56,681 --> 00:46:59,884
-It's a miracle!
-Anti-gravity clamps! Didn't I say?

811
00:47:00,217 --> 00:47:01,385
Round we go!

812
00:47:01,485 --> 00:47:02,620
(EXCLAIMING)

813
00:47:11,429 --> 00:47:13,831
Doctor! They're coming!

814
00:47:19,904 --> 00:47:23,407
I will never surrender. Never.

815
00:47:25,309 --> 00:47:27,411
Do you think this thing
will survive the journey back?

816
00:47:27,511 --> 00:47:31,782
-Only one way to find out! Next stop...
-Planet Earth!

817
00:47:38,989 --> 00:47:41,125
(ALL YELLING)

818
00:47:58,476 --> 00:48:01,679
-It's London!
-We're back home!

819
00:48:02,446 --> 00:48:04,515
He did it! He did it!

820
00:48:14,558 --> 00:48:15,760
Captain!

821
00:48:16,594 --> 00:48:19,897
Captain! They're back!
It's the bus, ma'am, it's come back.

822
00:48:19,997 --> 00:48:21,365
And it's flying!

823
00:48:32,076 --> 00:48:33,978
Code Red! Fire at will!

824
00:48:37,348 --> 00:48:38,749
(SCREECHING)

825
00:48:39,784 --> 00:48:41,552
(BULLETS ZIPPING)

826
00:48:43,120 --> 00:48:44,355
(MOBILE PHONE RINGS)

827
00:48:45,089 --> 00:48:49,393
-Malcolm! Close that wormhole.
-Yes, sir! My pleasure, sir!

828
00:48:52,329 --> 00:48:53,831
He's hung up on me!

829
00:48:54,999 --> 00:48:56,066
Yes!

830
00:48:56,667 --> 00:48:58,769
No, no, no!

831
00:49:08,746 --> 00:49:10,181
(MOBILE PHONE RINGS)

832
00:49:10,915 --> 00:49:13,551
-Malcolm?
-Not now, I'm busy!

833
00:49:15,753 --> 00:49:16,821
He's hung up again!

834
00:49:16,921 --> 00:49:18,456
(MOBILE PHONE RINGS)

835
00:49:18,556 --> 00:49:21,325
-Malcolm! Listen to me!
-It's not working!

836
00:49:21,425 --> 00:49:24,261
I need that signal, we've got billions
of those things about to fly through!

837
00:49:24,361 --> 00:49:25,930
Well, what do I do?

838
00:49:26,030 --> 00:49:29,400
Loop it back through the integrator
and keep the signal ramping up!

839
00:49:29,500 --> 00:49:34,572
-By how much?
-500 Bernards! Do it now!

840
00:49:36,841 --> 00:49:37,908
Yes!

841
00:49:49,186 --> 00:49:51,121
SOLDIER: Maintain rapid fire!

842
00:49:51,188 --> 00:49:52,523
Fire!

843
00:49:56,827 --> 00:49:58,562
(FIRING CONTINUES)

844
00:49:59,830 --> 00:50:00,998
Yes!

845
00:50:08,205 --> 00:50:09,607
Target at nine o'clock!

846
00:50:13,811 --> 00:50:16,146
I don't believe it, guns don't work!

847
00:50:17,481 --> 00:50:18,782
(PEOPLE EXCLAIMING)

848
00:50:18,883 --> 00:50:20,551
Doctor, it's coming for us!

849
00:50:20,651 --> 00:50:22,419
(ALL YELLING)

850
00:50:25,422 --> 00:50:26,991
Oh, no, you don't!

851
00:50:29,393 --> 00:50:30,528
(CRASHING)

852
00:50:30,628 --> 00:50:32,229
(ALL SCREAMING)

853
00:50:34,798 --> 00:50:37,301
-Twelve o'clock! Take it out!
-SOLDIER: Fire!

854
00:50:42,039 --> 00:50:43,240
(CRASHING)

855
00:50:43,674 --> 00:50:46,944
-Cease fire! Arms down!
-SOLDIER: Cease fire!

856
00:50:49,880 --> 00:50:51,582
Did I say I hated you?

857
00:50:52,883 --> 00:50:54,251
I was lying.

858
00:50:54,351 --> 00:50:56,053
(ALL SIGHING WITH RELIEF)

859
00:51:05,229 --> 00:51:08,465
Do not stand forward of this point.
Ladies and gentlemen,

860
00:51:08,566 --> 00:51:14,071
you have reached your final destination.
Welcome home, the mighty 200!

861
00:51:14,805 --> 00:51:15,706
(BELL DINGING)

862
00:51:33,023 --> 00:51:34,792
(ALL LAUGHING)

863
00:51:52,443 --> 00:51:55,012
Welcome back, everyone.
If you could step away from the bus,

864
00:51:55,112 --> 00:51:58,215
just to be safe. As fast as you can,
thank you.

865
00:51:58,315 --> 00:51:59,984
It's standard procedure,
we need to screen you

866
00:52:00,084 --> 00:52:01,485
then you'll all be taken for debriefing.

867
00:52:01,585 --> 00:52:03,187
-I don't count.
-No, but, Doctor...

868
00:52:03,287 --> 00:52:04,888
With me, ma'am.

869
00:52:07,891 --> 00:52:10,694
-Doctor!
-You must be Malcolm!

870
00:52:10,761 --> 00:52:12,463
Oh! Oh!

871
00:52:13,063 --> 00:52:14,531
Oh, I love you.

872
00:52:17,067 --> 00:52:20,771
I love you. I love you.

873
00:52:21,372 --> 00:52:23,073
To your station, Dr Taylor.

874
00:52:26,110 --> 00:52:27,277
Yes, ma'am.

875
00:52:31,682 --> 00:52:32,916
I love you.

876
00:52:39,823 --> 00:52:44,495
Doctor, I salute you,
whether you like it or not.

877
00:52:45,229 --> 00:52:47,531
Now, I take it
we're safe from those things?

878
00:52:47,631 --> 00:52:50,067
They'll start again.
Generate a new doorway.

879
00:52:50,167 --> 00:52:52,336
It's not their fault,
it's their natural life cycle.

880
00:52:52,436 --> 00:52:56,573
But I'll see if I can nudge
the wormholes on to uninhabited planets.

881
00:52:57,441 --> 00:53:00,678
Closer to home, Captain. Those two lads,

882
00:53:01,512 --> 00:53:03,247
very good in a crisis.

883
00:53:03,647 --> 00:53:07,284
Nathan needs a job, Barclay's good
with engines, you could do a lot worse.

884
00:53:07,384 --> 00:53:09,987
Privates Nathan and Barclay,
UNIT's finest.

885
00:53:10,654 --> 00:53:12,222
(MACHINE BEEPING)

886
00:53:12,322 --> 00:53:14,525
MAGAMBO: I'll see what I can do.

887
00:53:14,625 --> 00:53:16,960
And I've got something for you.

888
00:53:17,027 --> 00:53:19,263
(LAUGHS)

889
00:53:19,997 --> 00:53:22,232
Better than a bus, any day! Hello!

890
00:53:23,233 --> 00:53:25,169
Found in the gardens
of Buckingham Palace.

891
00:53:25,269 --> 00:53:26,704
Oh, she doesn't mind.

892
00:53:27,638 --> 00:53:31,175
Now, I've got three dead
alien stingrays to clear up.

893
00:53:31,275 --> 00:53:33,243
I don't suppose you fancy
helping with the paperwork?

894
00:53:33,310 --> 00:53:34,778
Not a chance!

895
00:53:34,878 --> 00:53:37,314
-Till we meet again, Doctor.
-I hope so.

896
00:53:38,549 --> 00:53:41,151
I said I'm back, Suzanne, I'm home!

897
00:53:43,353 --> 00:53:45,389
Didn't even know I was gone!

898
00:53:45,489 --> 00:53:46,657
(DEVICE WARBLING)

899
00:53:46,757 --> 00:53:48,892
That's quite enough of that!

900
00:53:50,728 --> 00:53:52,996
She is not getting away this time.

901
00:53:54,198 --> 00:53:56,633
Little, blue box! Just like you said.

902
00:53:57,067 --> 00:54:01,338
Right, then, off we go!
Come on, Doctor, show me the stars!

903
00:54:01,438 --> 00:54:03,640
-No.
-What?

904
00:54:04,708 --> 00:54:07,144
-I said no.
-But I saved your life.

905
00:54:07,478 --> 00:54:09,346
-And you saved mine.
-So?

906
00:54:09,913 --> 00:54:12,816
We're surrounded by police.
I'll go to prison.

907
00:54:12,916 --> 00:54:14,485
-Yeah.
-But you were right,

908
00:54:14,585 --> 00:54:18,455
it's not about the money,
I only steal things for the adventure,

909
00:54:18,956 --> 00:54:22,392
and today, with you,
I want more days like this.

910
00:54:22,893 --> 00:54:25,229
I want every day to be like this.

911
00:54:25,596 --> 00:54:28,132
We're made for each other,
you said so yourself.

912
00:54:28,232 --> 00:54:29,733
The perfect team.

913
00:54:34,805 --> 00:54:36,073
Why not?

914
00:54:37,474 --> 00:54:40,577
People have travelled with me
and I've lost them.

915
00:54:41,678 --> 00:54:44,481
Lost them all. Never again.

916
00:54:46,950 --> 00:54:51,388
Lady Christina de Souza!
Oh, I've waited a long time to say this.

917
00:54:51,488 --> 00:54:55,058
I'm arresting you on suspicion of theft.

918
00:54:55,159 --> 00:54:58,028
You do not have to say anything,
et cetera, et cetera.

919
00:54:58,128 --> 00:54:59,997
Dennison, take her away!

920
00:55:07,471 --> 00:55:10,808
Doctor? You take care, now.

921
00:55:10,908 --> 00:55:15,245
-You, too! Chops and gravy, lovely!
-No, but you be careful.

922
00:55:16,146 --> 00:55:18,549
Because your song is ending, sir.

923
00:55:20,083 --> 00:55:22,853
-What do you mean?
-It is returning.

924
00:55:24,054 --> 00:55:28,358
It is returning through the dark.
And then, Doctor...

925
00:55:29,927 --> 00:55:31,395
Oh, but then...

926
00:55:33,297 --> 00:55:36,366
He will knock four times.

927
00:55:52,516 --> 00:55:55,118
Alpha, alpha, five-one, alpha.

928
00:56:03,160 --> 00:56:04,595
(MECHANICAL BUZZING)

929
00:56:21,078 --> 00:56:24,114
-Hey!
-Hey, no, no! Stop that woman!

930
00:56:25,115 --> 00:56:28,652
Stop that woman! Stop her!

931
00:56:29,419 --> 00:56:31,855
Don't just stand there! Stop her!

932
00:56:35,792 --> 00:56:38,428
Open the door!
I'll add resisting arrest!

933
00:56:38,528 --> 00:56:40,564
I'd stand back, if I were you.

934
00:56:41,198 --> 00:56:43,734
I'm charging you, too!
Aiding and abetting!

935
00:56:43,834 --> 00:56:48,438
Yes, I'll just step inside
this police box and arrest myself.

936
00:56:51,708 --> 00:56:53,377
Out! Now!

937
00:56:55,879 --> 00:56:57,547
(WHIRRING)

938
00:57:09,126 --> 00:57:13,230
-No! Come back!
-Go on!

939
00:57:15,198 --> 00:57:16,500
(LAUGHING)

940
00:57:27,244 --> 00:57:32,316
-We could've been so good together.
-Christina, we were.

941
00:57:43,860 --> 00:57:45,362
(CHEERING)

942
00:58:27,170 --> 00:58:29,373
State your name, rank and intention.

943
00:58:32,042 --> 00:58:33,577
(SCREAMING)

944
00:58:45,088 --> 00:58:47,057
WOMAN: They're on the roof.

945
00:58:47,124 --> 00:58:48,525
(TRICKLING)

946
00:58:48,992 --> 00:58:50,327
Water always wins.

